SIMPLE: estuary
RECORDS: 2

==== ENTRY 1 ====
HEADWORD: Estuary
<hw>Es"tu*a*ry</hw> <pr>(?)</pr>, <pos>n.</pos>; <plu><it>pl.</it>
<plw>Estuaries</plw> <pr>(#)</pr>.</plu> <ety>[L. <ets>aestuarium</ets>,
from <ets>aestuare</ets> to surge. See <er>Estuate</er>.]</ety>
<altsp>[Written also <asp>⟦ae⟧stuary</asp>.]</altsp> <sn>1.</sn> <def>A
place where water boils up; a spring that wells forth.</def>
<mark>[Obs.]</mark> <rj><au>Boyle.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><sn>2.</sn> <def>A passage, as the mouth of a river or lake, where
the tide meets the current; an arm of the sea; a frith.</def>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><q>it to the sea was often by long and wide <qex>estuaries</qex>.</q>
<rj><qau>Dana.</qau></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estuary</ent>⟦br⟧

==== ENTRY 2 ====
HEADWORD: Estuary
<hw>Es"tu*a*ry</hw>, <pos>a.</pos> <def>Belonging to, or formed in, an
estuary; <as>as, <ex>estuary</ex> strata</as>.</def>
<rj><au>Lyell.</au></rj>⟦br⟧
[<source>1913 Webster</source>]</p>

<p><ent>Estuate</ent>⟦br⟧
